# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emc-emi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In electronics, **crosstalk** (**XT**) is a phenomenon by which a signal transmitted on one circuit or channel of a transmission system creates an undesired effect in another circuit or channel.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Crosstalk is usually caused by undesired capacitive, inductive, or conductive coupling from one circuit or channel to another.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Where the electric, magnetic, or traveling fields of two electric signals overlap, the electromagnetic interference created causes crosstalk.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] For example, crosstalk can comprise magnetic fields that induce a smaller signal in neighboring wires.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In electrical circuits sharing a common signal return path, electrical impedance in the return path creates **common impedance coupling** between the signals, resulting in crosstalk.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Crosstalk is a significant issue in structured cabling, audio electronics, integrated circuit design, wireless communication and other communications systems.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In structured cabling, crosstalk refers to electromagnetic interference from one unshielded twisted pair to another twisted pair, normally running in parallel.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Signals traveling through adjacent pairs of wire create magnetic fields that interact with each other, inducing interference in the neighboring pair.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] The pair causing the interference is called the *disturbing pair*, while the pair experiencing the interference is the *disturbed pair*.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] NEXT is a measure of the ability of a cable to reject crosstalk, so the higher the NEXT value, the greater the rejection of crosstalk at the local connection.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] because the interference between the two signals in the cable is measured at the same end of the cable as the interfering transmitter.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] The NEXT value for a given cable type is generally expressed in decibels per feet or decibels per 1000 feet and varies with the frequency of transmission.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] General specifications for cabling (such as CAT 5) usually include the minimum NEXT values.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] PSNEXT is a NEXT measurement which includes the sum of crosstalk contributions from all adjacent pairs as an algebraic sum of the NEXT of the three wire pairs as they affect the fourth pair in a four-pair cable (e.g., Category 6 cable).
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] states that the testing process for PSNEXT consists of measuring all pair-to-pair crosstalk combinations and then summing all of the values for each pair.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] The specification was developed to directly address the effect of transmissions on multiple adjacent pairs on the pair being tested and is relevant to all connecting hardware and associated communications cables.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] uses all four wire pairs simultaneously and bidirectionally.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] The additional wire pair usage and growing bandwidth increases the need to keep NEXT in check.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] FEXT measures the interference between two pairs of a cable measured at the far end of the cable with respect to the interfering transmitter.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] ELFEXT measures the FEXT with attenuation compensation.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] AXT is interference caused by other cables routed close to the cable of interest as opposed to signals contained in the same cable.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In stereo audio reproduction, crosstalk can refer to signal leakage across from one program channel to another, reducing channel separation and stereo imaging.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Crosstalk between channels in mixing consoles, and between studio feeds is a much more noticeable problem, as these are likely to be carrying very different programs or material.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Crosstalk is an electrical effect and can be quantified with a crosstalk measurement.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Crosstalk measurements are made on audio systems to determine the amount of signal leaking from one channel to another.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] The Independent Broadcasting Authority published a weighting curve for use in crosstalk measurement that gives due emphasis to the subjective audibility of different frequencies.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In the absence of any international standards, this is still in use despite the demise of the IBA.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Good crosstalk performance for a stereo system is not difficult to achieve in today's digital audio systems, though it is difficult to keep below the desired figure of −30 dB or so on vinyl recordings and FM radio.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In telecommunication or telephony, crosstalk is often distinguishable as pieces of speech or in-band signaling tones leaking from other people's connections.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] If the connection is analog, twisted pair cabling can often be used to reduce crosstalk.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Alternatively, the signals can be converted to digital form, which is typically less susceptible to crosstalk.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In wireless communication, crosstalk is often denoted co-channel interference, and is related to adjacent-channel interference.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In integrated circuit design, crosstalk normally refers to a signal affecting another nearby signal.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] Usually, the coupling is capacitive, and to the nearest neighbor, but other forms of coupling and effects on signal further away are sometimes important, especially in analog designs.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] See signal integrity for tools used to measure and prevent this problem, and substrate coupling for a discussion of crosstalk conveyed through the integrated circuit substrate.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] There are a wide variety of repair solutions, with increased spacing, wire re-ordering, and shielding being the most common.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In full-field optical coherence tomography, "crosstalk" refers to the phenomenon that due to highly scattering objects, multiple scattered photons reach the image plane and generate a coherent signal after travelling a path length that matches that of the sample depth within a coherence length.
[src:emc-emi/crosstalk] In stereoscopic 3D displays, crosstalk refers to the incomplete isolation of the left and right image channels so that one bleeds into the other – like a double exposure, which produces a ghosting effect.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC pursues three main classes of issue.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Emission* is the generation of electromagnetic energy, whether deliberate or accidental, by some source and its release into the environment.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC studies the unwanted emissions and the countermeasures which may be taken in order to reduce unwanted emissions.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The second class, *susceptibility*, is the tendency of electrical equipment, referred to as the victim, to malfunction or break down in the presence of unwanted emissions, which are known as radio-frequency interference (RFI).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Immunity* is the opposite of susceptibility, being the ability of equipment to function correctly in the presence of RFI, with the discipline of "hardening" equipment being known equally as susceptibility or immunity.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] A third class studied is *coupling*, which is the mechanism by which emitted interference reaches the victim.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Interference mitigation and hence electromagnetic compatibility may be achieved by addressing any or all of these issues, i.e., quieting the sources of interference, inhibiting coupling paths and/or hardening the potential victims.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In practice, many of the engineering techniques used, such as grounding and shielding, apply to all three issues.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The earliest EMC issue was lightning strike (lightning electromagnetic pulse, or LEMP) on ships and buildings.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Lightning rods or lightning conductors began to appear in the mid-18th century.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] With the advent of widespread electricity generation and power supply lines from the late 19th century on, problems also arose with equipment short-circuit failure affecting the power supply, and with local fire and shock hazard when the power line was struck by lightning.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Power stations were provided with output circuit breakers.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Buildings and appliances would soon be provided with input fuses, and later in the 20th century miniature circuit breakers (MCB) would come into use.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] It may be said that radio interference and its correction arose with the first spark-gap experiment of Marconi in the late 1800s.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] As radio communications developed in the first half of the 20th century, interference between broadcast radio signals began to occur and an international regulatory framework was set up to ensure interference-free communications.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Switching devices became commonplace through the middle of the 20th century, typically in petrol powered cars and motorcycles but also in domestic appliances such as thermostats and refrigerators.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This caused transient interference with domestic radio and (after World War II) TV reception, and in due course laws were passed requiring the suppression of such interference sources.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge (ESD) problems first arose with accidental electric spark discharges in hazardous environments such as coal mines and when refuelling aircraft or motor cars.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Safe working practices had to be developed.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] After World War II the military became increasingly concerned with the effects of nuclear electromagnetic pulse (NEMP), lightning strike, and even high-powered radar beams, on vehicle and mobile equipment of all kinds, and especially aircraft electrical systems.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] When high RF emission levels from other sources became a potential problem (such as with the advent of microwave ovens), certain frequency bands were designated for Industrial, Scientific and Medical (ISM) use, allowing emission levels limited only by thermal safety standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Later, the International Telecommunication Union adopted a Recommendation providing limits of radiation from ISM devices in order to protect radiocommunications.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] A variety of issues such as sideband and harmonic emissions, broadband sources, and the ever-increasing popularity of electrical switching devices and their victims, resulted in a steady development of standards and laws.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the late 1970s, the popularity of modern digital circuitry rapidly grew.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] As the technology developed, with ever-faster switching speeds (increasing emissions) and lower circuit voltages (increasing susceptibility), EMC increasingly became a source of concern.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Many more nations became aware of EMC as a growing problem and issued directives to the manufacturers of digital electronic equipment, which set out the essential manufacturer requirements before their equipment could be marketed or sold.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Organizations in individual nations, across Europe and worldwide, were set up to maintain these directives and associated standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1979, the American FCC published a regulation that required the electromagnetic emissions of all "digital devices" to be below certain limits.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This regulatory environment led to a sharp growth in the EMC industry supplying specialist devices and equipment, analysis and design software, and testing and certification services.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Low-voltage digital circuits, especially CMOS transistors, became more susceptible to ESD damage as they were miniaturised and, despite the development of on-chip hardening techniques, a new ESD regulatory regime had to be developed.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the 1980s on the explosive growth in mobile communications and broadcast media channels put huge pressure on the available airspace.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Regulatory authorities began squeezing band allocations closer and closer together, relying on increasingly sophisticated EMC control methods, especially in the digital communications domain, to keep cross-channel interference to acceptable levels.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Digital systems are inherently less susceptible than analogue systems, and also offer far easier ways (such as software) to implement highly sophisticated protection and error-correction measures.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1985, the USA released the ISM bands for low-power mobile digital communications, leading to the development of Wi-Fi and remotely-operated car door keys.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This approach relies on the intermittent nature of ISM interference and use of sophisticated error-correction methods to ensure lossless reception during the quiet gaps between any bursts of interference.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC ensures the correct operation, in the same electromagnetic environment, of different equipment items which use or respond to electromagnetic phenomena, and the avoidance of any interference.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Another way of saying this is that EMC is the control of EMI so that unwanted effects are prevented.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Besides understanding the phenomena in themselves, EMC also addresses the countermeasures, such as control regimes, design and measurement, which should be taken in order to prevent emissions from causing any adverse effect.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC is often understood as the control of electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electromagnetic interference divides into several categories according to the source and signal characteristics.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be man-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference comprises a given range of frequencies.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This type is naturally divided into sub-categories according to frequency range, and as a whole is sometimes referred to as "DC to daylight".
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] One common classification is into narrowband and broadband, according to the spread of the frequency range.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, is a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pulse signals divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] When a source emits interference, it follows a route to the victim known as the coupling path.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] There are four basic coupling mechanisms: conductive, capacitive, magnetic or inductive, and radiative.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Any coupling path can be broken down into one or more of these coupling mechanisms working together.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Source and victim act as radio antennas: the source emits or radiates an electromagnetic wave which propagates across the space in between and is picked up or received by the victim.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The damaging effects of electromagnetic interference pose unacceptable risks in many areas of technology, and it is necessary to control such interference and reduce the risks to acceptable levels.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The risk posed by the threat is usually statistical in nature, so much of the work in threat characterisation and standards setting is based on reducing the probability of disruptive EMI to an acceptable level, rather than its assured elimination.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] For a complex or novel piece of equipment, this may require the production of a dedicated *EMC control plan* summarizing the application of the above and specifying additional documents required.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Breaking a coupling path is equally effective at either the start or the end of the path, therefore many aspects of good EMC design practice apply equally to potential sources and to potential victims.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] A design which easily couples energy to the outside world will equally easily couple energy in and will be susceptible.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] A single improvement will often reduce both emissions and susceptibility.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Grounding and shielding aim to reduce emissions or divert EMI away from the victim by providing an alternative, low-impedance path.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Testing is required to confirm that a particular device meets the required standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] It is divided broadly into emissions testing and susceptibility testing.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Open-area test sites, or OATS, are the reference sites in most standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] They are especially useful for emissions testing of large equipment systems.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] However, RF testing of a physical prototype is most often carried out indoors, in a specialized EMC test chamber.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Types of the chamber include anechoic, reverberation and the gigahertz transverse electromagnetic cell (GTEM cell).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Sometimes computational electromagnetics simulations are used to test virtual models.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Like all compliance testing, it is important that the test equipment, including the test chamber or site and any software used, be properly calibrated and maintained.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typically, a given run of tests for a particular piece of equipment will require an *EMC test plan* and a follow-up *test report*.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The full test program may require the production of several such documents.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Emissions are typically measured for radiated field strength and where appropriate for conducted emissions along cables and wiring.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive (magnetic) and capacitive (electric) field strengths are near-field effects and are only important if the device under test (DUT) is designed for a location close to other electrical equipment.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] For conducted emissions, typical transducers include the LISN (line impedance stabilization network) or AMN (artificial mains network) and the RF current clamp.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] For radiated emission measurement, antennas are used as transducers.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typical antennas specified include dipole, biconical, log-periodic, double ridged guide and conical log-spiral designs.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated emissions must be measured in all directions around the DUT.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Specialized EMI test receivers or EMI analyzers are used for EMC compliance testing.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] These incorporate bandwidths and detectors as specified by international EMC standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] An EMI receiver may be based on a spectrum analyser to measure the emission levels of the DUT across a wide band of frequencies (frequency domain), or on a tunable narrower-band device which is swept through the desired frequency range.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMI receivers along with specified transducers can often be used for both conducted and radiated emissions.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pre-selector filters may also be used to reduce the effect of strong out-of-band signals on the front-end of the receiver.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some pulse emissions are more usefully characterized using an oscilloscope to capture the pulse waveform in the time domain.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated field susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered source of RF or EM energy and a radiating antenna to direct the energy at the potential victim or device under test (DUT).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conducted voltage and current susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered signal generator, and a current clamp or other type of transformer to inject the test signal.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Transient or EMP signals are used to test the immunity of the DUT against powerline disturbances including surges, lightning strikes and switching noise.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In motor vehicles, similar tests are performed on battery and signal lines.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The transient pulse may be generated digitally and passed through a broadband pulse amplifier, or applied directly to the transducer from a specialized pulse generator.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge testing is typically performed with a piezo spark generator called an "ESD pistol".
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Higher energy pulses, such as lightning or nuclear EMP simulations, can require a large current clamp or a large antenna which completely surrounds the DUT.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some antennas are so large that they are located outdoors, and care must be taken not to cause an EMP hazard to the surrounding environment.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Several organizations, both national and international, work to promote international co-operation on standardization (harmonization), including publishing various EMC standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Where possible, a standard developed by one organization may be adopted with little or no change by others.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] This helps for example to harmonize national standards across Europe.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with national or international standards is usually laid down by laws passed by individual nations.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Different nations can require compliance with different standards.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In European law, EU directive 2014/30/EU (previously 2004/108/EC) on EMC defines the rules for the placing on the market/putting into service of electric/electronic equipment within the European Union.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] The Directive applies to a vast range of equipment including electrical and electronic appliances, systems and installations.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Manufacturers of electric and electronic devices are advised to run EMC tests in order to comply with compulsory CE-labeling.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] More are given in the list of EMC directives.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with the applicable harmonised standards whose reference is listed in the OJEU under the EMC Directive gives presumption of conformity with the corresponding essential requirements of the EMC Directive.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 2019, the USA adopted a program for the protection of critical infrastructure against an electromagnetic pulse, whether caused by a geomagnetic storm or a high-altitude nuclear weapon.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Both human-made and natural sources generate changing electrical currents and voltages that can cause EMI: ignition systems, cellular network of mobile phones, lightning, solar flares, and auroras (northern/southern lights).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] It can also affect mobile phones, FM radios, and televisions, as well as observations for radio astronomy and atmospheric science.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] EMI can be used intentionally for radio jamming, as in electronic warfare.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Since the earliest days of radio communications, the negative effects of interference from both intentional and unintentional transmissions have been felt and the need to manage the radio frequency spectrum became apparent.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In 1933, a meeting of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in Paris recommended the International Special Committee on Radio Interference (CISPR) be set up to deal with the emerging problem of EMI.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] CISPR subsequently produced technical publications covering measurement and test techniques and recommended emission and immunity limits.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These have evolved over the decades and form the basis of much of the world's EMC regulations today.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In 1979, legal limits were imposed on electromagnetic emissions from all digital equipment by the FCC in the US in response to the increased number of digital systems that were interfering with wired and radio communications.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Test methods and limits were based on CISPR publications, although similar limits were already enforced in parts of Europe.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In the mid 1980s, the European Union member states adopted a number of "new approach" directives with the intention of standardizing technical requirements for products so that they do not become a barrier to trade within the EC.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] One of these was the EMC Directive (89/336/EC) and it applies to all equipment placed on the market or taken into service.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Its scope covers all apparatus "liable to cause electromagnetic disturbance or the performance of which is liable to be affected by such disturbance".
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This was the first time there was a legal requirement on immunity, as well as emissions on apparatus intended for the general population.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Although there may be additional costs involved for some products to give them a known level of immunity, it increases their perceived quality as they are able to co-exist with apparatus in the active EM environment of modern times and with fewer problems.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Many countries now have similar requirements for products to meet some level of electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) regulation.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be human-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference arises where the source continuously emits at a given range of frequencies.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, arises where the source emits a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Sources divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted electromagnetic interference is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI, which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic disturbances in the EM field of a conductor will no longer be confined to the surface of the conductor and will radiate away from it.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This persists in all conductors and mutual inductance between two radiated electromagnetic fields will result in EMI.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the technical terms which are employed can be used with differing meanings.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Some phenomena may be referred to by various different terms.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These terms are used here in a widely accepted way, which is consistent with other articles in the encyclopedia.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The basic arrangement of noise emitter or source, coupling path and victim, receptor or sink is shown in the figure below.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Source and victim are usually electronic hardware devices, though the source may be a natural phenomenon such as a lightning strike, electrostatic discharge (ESD) or, in one famous case, the Big Bang at the origin of the Universe.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] For example the lower path in the diagram involves inductive, conductive and capacitive modes.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body, for example a transmission line, wire, cable, PCB trace or metal enclosure.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling occurs where the source and victim are separated by a short distance (typically less than a wavelength).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Strictly, "Inductive coupling" can be of two kinds, electrical induction and magnetic induction.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] It is common to refer to electrical induction as *capacitive coupling*, and to magnetic induction as *inductive coupling*.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance, typically more than a wavelength.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This is also a definition used by the frequency administration to provide frequency assignments and assignment of frequency channels to radio stations or systems, as well as to analyze electromagnetic compatibility between radiocommunication services.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted EMI is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] For lower frequencies, EMI is caused by conduction and, for higher frequencies, by radiation.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] EMI through the ground wire is also very common in an electrical facility.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Interference tends to be more troublesome with older radio technologies such as analogue amplitude modulation, which have no way of distinguishing unwanted in-band signals from the intended signal, and the omnidirectional antennas used with broadcast systems.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Newer radio systems incorporate several improvements that enhance the selectivity.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In digital radio systems, such as Wi-Fi, error-correction techniques can be used.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Spread-spectrum and frequency-hopping techniques can be used with both analogue and digital signalling to improve resistance to interference.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] A highly directional receiver, such as a parabolic antenna or a diversity receiver, can be used to select one signal in space to the exclusion of others.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The most extreme example of digital spread-spectrum signalling to date is ultra-wideband (UWB), which proposes the use of large sections of the radio spectrum at low amplitudes to transmit high-bandwidth digital data.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In the United States, the 1982 Public Law 97-259 allowed the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to regulate the susceptibility of consumer electronic equipment.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Potential sources of RFI and EMI include: various types of transmitters, doorbell transformers, toaster ovens, electric blankets, ultrasonic pest control devices, electric bug zappers, heating pads, and touch controlled lamps.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Multiple CRT computer monitors or televisions sitting too close to one another can sometimes cause a "shimmy" effect in each other, due to the electromagnetic nature of their picture tubes, especially when one of their de-gaussing coils is activated.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic interference at 2.4 GHz may be caused by 802.11b, 802.11g and 802.11n wireless devices, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors and cordless telephones, video senders, and microwave ovens.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Switching loads (inductive, capacitive, and resistive), such as electric motors, transformers, heaters, lamps, ballast, power supplies, etc., all cause electromagnetic interference especially at currents above 2 A.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The usual method used for suppressing EMI is by connecting a snubber network, a resistor in series with a capacitor, across a pair of contacts.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] While this may offer modest EMI reduction at very low currents, snubbers do not work at currents over 2 A with electromechanical contacts.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Another method for suppressing EMI is the use of ferrite core noise suppressors (or ferrite beads), which are inexpensive and which clip on to the power lead of the offending device or the compromised device.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Switched-mode power supplies can be a source of EMI, but have become less of a problem as design techniques have improved, such as integrated power factor correction.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Most countries have legal requirements that mandate electromagnetic compatibility: electronic and electrical hardware must still work correctly when subjected to certain amounts of EMI, and should not emit EMI, which could interfere with other equipment (such as radios).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Radio frequency signal quality has declined throughout the 21st century by roughly one decibel per year as the spectrum becomes increasingly crowded.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This has inflicted a Red Queen's race on the mobile phone industry as companies have been forced to put up more cellular towers (at new frequencies) that then cause more interference thereby requiring more investment by the providers and frequent upgrades of mobile phones to match.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These are civilian standards for domestic, commercial, industrial and automotive sectors.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These standards form the basis of other national or regional standards, most notably the European Norms (EN) written by CENELEC (European committee for electrotechnical standardisation).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] US organizations include the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the American National Standards Institute (ANSI), and the US Military (MILSTD).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Integrated circuits are often a source of EMI, but they must usually couple their energy to larger objects such as heatsinks, circuit board planes and cables to radiate significantly.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] On integrated circuits, important means of reducing EMI are: the use of bypass or decoupling capacitors on each active device (connected across the power supply, as close to the device as possible), rise time control of high-speed signals using series resistors, and IC power supply pin filtering.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Shielding is usually a last resort after other techniques have failed, because of the added expense of shielding components such as conductive gaskets.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] At lower frequencies, such as 133 MHz, radiation is almost exclusively via I/O cables; RF noise gets onto the power planes and is coupled to the line drivers via the VCC and GND pins.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The RF is then coupled to the cable through the line driver as common-mode noise.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Since the noise is common-mode, shielding has very little effect, even with differential pairs.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The RF energy is capacitively coupled from the signal pair to the shield and the shield itself does the radiating.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] One cure for this is to use a braid-breaker or choke to reduce the common-mode signal.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] At higher frequencies, usually above 500 MHz, traces get electrically longer and higher above the plane.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Two techniques are used at these frequencies: wave shaping with series resistors and embedding the traces between the two planes.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] If all these measures still leave too much EMI, shielding such as RF gaskets and copper or conductive tape can be used.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Most digital equipment is designed with metal or conductive-coated plastic cases.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Any unshielded semiconductor (e.g. an integrated circuit) will tend to act as a detector for those radio signals commonly found in the domestic environment (e.g. mobile phones).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Such a detector can demodulate the high frequency mobile phone carrier (e.g., GSM850 and GSM1900, GSM900 and GSM1800) and produce low-frequency (e.g., 217 Hz) demodulated signals.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This demodulation manifests itself as unwanted audible buzz in audio appliances such as microphone amplifier, speaker amplifier, car radio, telephones etc.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Adding onboard EMI filters or special layout techniques can help in bypassing EMI or improving RF immunity.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Some ICs are designed (e.g., LMV831-LMV834, MAX9724) to have integrated RF filters or a special design that helps reduce any demodulation of high-frequency carrier.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Designers often need to carry out special tests for RF immunity of parts to be used in a system.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These tests are often done in an anechoic chamber with a controlled RF environment where the test vectors produce a RF field similar to that produced in an actual environment.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Interference in radio astronomy, where it is commonly referred to as radio-frequency interference (RFI), is any source of transmission that is within the observed frequency band other than the celestial sources themselves.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Because transmitters on and around the Earth can be many times stronger than the astronomical signal of interest, RFI is a major concern for performing radio astronomy.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the frequency bands that are very important for radio astronomy, such as the 21-cm HI line at 1420 MHz, are protected by regulation.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] However, modern radio-astronomical observatories such as VLA, LOFAR, and ALMA have a very large bandwidth over which they can observe.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Techniques to deal with RFI range from filters in hardware to advanced algorithms in software.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] One way to deal with strong transmitters is to filter out the frequency of the source completely.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This is for example the case for the LOFAR observatory, which filters out the FM radio stations between 90 and 110 MHz.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] It is important to remove such strong sources of interference as soon as possible, because they might "saturate" the highly sensitive receivers (amplifiers and analogue-to-digital converters), which means that the received signal is stronger than the receiver can handle.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] However, filtering out a frequency band implies that these frequencies can never be observed with the instrument.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] A common technique to deal with RFI within the observed frequency bandwidth, is to employ RFI detection in software.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Such software can find samples in time, frequency or time-frequency space that are contaminated by an interfering source.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These samples are subsequently ignored in further analysis of the observed data.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] This process is often referred to as *data flagging*.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Because most transmitters have a small bandwidth and are not continuously present such as lightning or citizens' band (CB) radio devices, most of the data remains available for the astronomical analysis.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] However, data flagging can not solve issues with continuous broad-band transmitters, such as windmills, digital video or digital audio transmitters.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Another way to manage RFI is to establish a radio quiet zone (RQZ).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] RQZ is a well-defined area surrounding receivers that has special regulations to reduce RFI in favor of radio astronomy observations within the zone.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The regulations may include special management of spectrum and power flux or power flux-density limitations.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The controls within the zone may cover elements other than radio transmitters or radio devices.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These include aircraft controls and control of unintentional radiators such as industrial, scientific and medical devices, vehicles, and power lines.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The first RQZ for radio astronomy is United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), established in 1958.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Prior to the introduction of Wi-Fi, one of the biggest applications of 5 GHz band was the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The decision to use 5 GHz spectrum for Wi-Fi was finalized at the World Radiocommunication Conference in 2003; however, meteorological authorities were not involved in the process.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] The subsequent lax implementation and misconfiguration of DFS had caused significant disruption in weather radar operations in a number of countries around the world.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] In Hungary, the weather radar system was declared non-operational for more than a month.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Due to the severity of interference, South African weather services ended up abandoning C band operation, switching their radar network to S band.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Transmissions on adjacent bands to those used by passive remote sensing, such as weather satellites, have caused interference, sometimes significant.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] There is concern that adoption of insufficiently regulated 5G could produce major interference issues.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] Significant interference can impair numerical weather prediction performance and incur negative economic and public safety impacts.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-interference] These concerns led US Secretary of Commerce Wilbur Ross and NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine in February 2019 to urge the FCC to cancel a proposed spectrum auction, which was rejected.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] In electrical engineering, **electromagnetic shielding** is the practice of reducing or redirecting the electromagnetic field (EMF) in a space with barriers made of conductive or magnetic materials.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] It is typically applied to enclosures, for isolating electrical devices from their surroundings, and to cables to isolate wires from the environment through which the cable runs ().
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic shielding that blocks radio frequency (RF) electromagnetic radiation is also known as **RF shielding**.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Practical field measurements in residential bedrooms typically use consumer EMF meters to determine local exposure levels.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] EMF shielding serves to minimize electromagnetic interference.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The shielding can reduce the coupling of radio waves, electromagnetic fields, and electrostatic fields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] A conductive enclosure used to block electrostatic fields is also known as a *Faraday cage*.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The amount of reduction depends very much upon the material used, its thickness, the size of the shielded volume and the frequency of the fields of interest and the size, shape and orientation of holes in a shield to an incident electromagnetic field.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Typical materials used for electromagnetic shielding include thin layer of metal, sheet metal, metal screen, and metal foam.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Common sheet metals for shielding include copper, brass, nickel, silver, steel, and tin.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Shielding effectiveness, that is, how well a shield reflects or absorbs/suppresses electromagnetic radiation, is affected by the physical properties of the metal.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] These may include conductivity, solderability, permeability, thickness, and weight.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] A metal's properties are an important consideration in material selection.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] For example, electrically dominant waves are reflected by highly conductive metals like copper, silver, and brass, while magnetically dominant waves are absorbed/suppressed by a less conductive metal such as steel or stainless steel.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Further, any holes in the shield or mesh must be significantly smaller than the wavelength of the radiation that is being kept out, or the enclosure will not effectively approximate an unbroken conducting surface.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Another commonly used shielding method, especially with electronic goods housed in plastic enclosures, is to coat the inside of the enclosure with a metallic ink or similar material.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The ink consists of a carrier material loaded with a suitable metal, typically copper or nickel, in the form of very small particulates.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] It is sprayed on to the enclosure and, once dry, produces a continuous conductive layer of metal, which can be electrically connected to the chassis ground of the equipment, thus providing effective shielding.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic shielding is the process of lowering the electromagnetic field in an area by barricading it with conductive or magnetic material.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Copper is used for radio frequency (RF) shielding because it absorbs radio and other electromagnetic waves.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Properly designed and constructed RF shielding enclosures satisfy most RF shielding needs, from computer and electrical switching rooms to hospital CAT-scan and MRI facilities.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] EMI (electromagnetic interference) shielding is of great research interest and several new types of nanocomposites made of ferrites, polymers, and 2D materials are being developed to obtain more efficient RF/microwave-absorbing materials (MAMs).
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] EMI shielding is often achieved by electroless plating of copper as most popular plastics are non-conductive or by special conductive paint.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] One example is a shielded cable, which has electromagnetic shielding in the form of a wire mesh surrounding an inner core conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The shielding impedes the escape of any signal from the core conductor, and also prevents signals from being added to the core conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Some cables have two separate coaxial screens, one connected at both ends, the other at one end only, to maximize shielding of both electromagnetic and electrostatic fields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The door of a microwave oven has a screen built into the window.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] From the perspective of microwaves (with wavelengths of 12 cm) this screen finishes a Faraday cage formed by the oven's metal housing.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Visible light, with wavelengths ranging between 400 nm and 700 nm, passes easily through the screen holes.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] RF shielding is also used to prevent access to data stored on RFID chips embedded in various devices, such as biometric passports.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] NATO specifies electromagnetic shielding for computers and keyboards to prevent passive monitoring of keyboard emissions that would allow passwords to be captured; consumer keyboards do not offer this protection primarily because of the prohibitive cost.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] RF shielding is also used to protect medical and laboratory equipment to provide protection against interfering signals, including AM, FM, TV, emergency services, dispatch, pagers, ESMR, cellular, and PCS.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] It can also be used to protect the equipment at the AM, FM or TV broadcast facilities.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Another example of the practical use of electromagnetic shielding would be defense applications.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] As technology improves, so does the susceptibility to various types of nefarious electromagnetic interference.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The idea of encasing a cable inside a grounded conductive barrier can provide mitigation to these risks.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic radiation consists of coupled electric and magnetic fields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The electric field produces forces on the charge carriers (i.e., electrons) within the conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] As soon as an electric field is applied to the surface of an ideal conductor, it induces a current that causes displacement of charge inside the conductor that cancels the applied field inside, at which point the current stops.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Similarly, *varying* magnetic fields generate eddy currents that act to cancel the applied magnetic field.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] (The conductor does not respond to static magnetic fields unless the conductor is moving relative to the magnetic field.) The result is that electromagnetic radiation is reflected from the surface of the conductor: internal fields stay inside, and external fields stay outside.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Several factors serve to limit the shielding capability of real RF shields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] One is that, due to the electrical resistance of the conductor, the excited field does not completely cancel the incident field.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Also, most conductors exhibit a ferromagnetic response to low-frequency magnetic fields, so that such fields are not fully attenuated by the conductor.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Any holes in the shield force current to flow around them, so that fields passing through the holes do not excite opposing electromagnetic fields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] These effects reduce the field-reflecting capability of the shield.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] This is one aspect of a greater phenomenon called the skin effect.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] A measure of the depth to which radiation can penetrate the shield is the so-called skin depth.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Equipment sometimes requires isolation from external magnetic fields.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] For static or slowly varying magnetic fields (below about 100 kHz) the Faraday shielding described above is ineffective.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] In these cases shields made of high magnetic permeability metal alloys can be used, such as sheets of permalloy and mu-metal or with nanocrystalline grain structure ferromagnetic metal coatings.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] These materials do not block the magnetic field, as with electric shielding, but rather draw the field into themselves, providing a path for the magnetic field lines around the shielded volume.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The best shape for magnetic shields is thus a closed container surrounding the shielded volume.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] The effectiveness of this type of shielding depends on the material's permeability, which generally drops off at both very low magnetic field strengths and high field strengths where the material becomes saturated.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Therefore, to achieve low residual fields, magnetic shields often consist of several enclosures, one inside the other, each of which successively reduces the field inside it.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Entry holes within shielding surfaces may degrade their performance significantly.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Because of the above limitations of passive shielding, an alternative used with static or low-frequency fields is active shielding, in which a field created by electromagnets cancels the ambient field within a volume.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Solenoids and Helmholtz coils are types of coils that can be used for this purpose, as well as more complex wire patterns designed using methods adapted from those used in coil design for magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Active shields may also be designed accounting for the electromagnetic coupling with passive shields, referred to as *hybrid* shielding, so that there is broadband shielding from the passive shield and additional cancellation of specific components using the active system.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Additionally, superconducting materials can expel magnetic fields via the Meissner effect.
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Suppose that we have a spherical shell of a (linear and isotropic) diamagnetic material with relative permeability $\mu _{\text{r}}$ , with inner radius a and outer radius b .
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] Notice that this coefficient appropriately goes to 1 (no shielding) in the limit that $\mu _{\text{r}}\to 1$ .
[src:emc-emi/electromagnetic-shielding] In the limit that $\mu _{\text{r}}\to \infty$ this coefficient goes to 0 (perfect shielding).
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] A **Faraday cage** or **Faraday shield** is an enclosure used to block some electromagnetic fields.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] A Faraday shield may be formed by a continuous covering of conductive material, or in the case of a Faraday cage, by a mesh of such materials.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are named after the scientist Michael Faraday, who first constructed one in 1836.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Faraday cages work because an external electrical field will cause the electric charges within the cage's conducting material to be distributed in a way that cancels out the field's effect inside the cage.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] This phenomenon can be used to protect sensitive electronic equipment (for example RF receivers) from external radio frequency interference (RFI), often during testing or alignment of the device.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are also used to protect people and equipment against electric currents such as lightning strikes and electrostatic discharges, because the cage conducts electrical current around the outside of the enclosed space and none passes through the interior.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Faraday cages cannot block stable or slowly varying magnetic fields, such as the Earth's magnetic field (a compass will still work inside one).
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] To a large degree, however, they shield the interior from external electromagnetic radiation if the conductor is thick enough and any hole is significantly smaller than the wavelength of the radiation.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] For example, certain computer forensic electronic systems test procedures that require an electromagnetic interference free environment can be carried out within a screened room.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] These rooms are spaces that are completely enclosed by one or more layers of a fine metal mesh or perforated sheet metal.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The metal layers are grounded to dissipate any electric currents generated from external or internal electromagnetic fields, and thus they block a large amount of the electromagnetic interference (see also electromagnetic shielding).
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Near-field, high-powered frequency transmissions like HF RFID are more likely to penetrate.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Solid cages generally attenuate fields over a broader frequency range than mesh cages.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] In 1754, Jean-Antoine Nollet published an account of the cage effect in his *Leçons de physique expérimentale*.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] In 1755, Benjamin Franklin observed the effect by lowering an uncharged cork ball suspended on a silk thread through an opening in an electrically charged metal can.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The behavior is that of a Faraday cage or shield.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] In 1836, Michael Faraday observed that the excess charge on a charged conductor resided only on its exterior and had no influence on anything enclosed within it.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] To demonstrate this, he built a metal foil-coated room and allowed high-voltage discharges from an electrostatic generator to strike the outside of the room.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] He used an electroscope to show that there was no electric charge present on the inside of the room walls.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] A continuous Faraday shield is a hollow conductor.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Externally or internally applied electromagnetic fields produce forces on the charge carriers (usually electrons) within the conductor; the charges are redistributed accordingly due to electrostatic induction.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The redistributed charges greatly reduce the voltage within the surface, to an extent depending on the capacitance; however, full cancellation does not occur.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] If charge $+Q$ is placed inside an ungrounded Faraday shield without touching the walls, the internal face of the shield becomes charged with $-Q$ , leading to field lines originating at the charge and extending to charges inside the inner surface of the metal.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The field line paths in this inside space (to the endpoint negative charges) are dependent on the shape of the inner containment walls.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Simultaneously $+Q$ accumulates on the outer face of the shield.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The spread of charges on the outer face is not affected by the position of the internal charge inside the enclosure, but rather determined by the shape of the outer face.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] So for all intents and purposes, the Faraday shield generates the same static electric field on the outside that it would generate if the metal were simply charged with $+Q$ .
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] See Faraday's ice pail experiment, for example, for more details on electric field lines and the decoupling of the outside from the inside.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Note that electromagnetic waves are not static charges.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] If the cage is grounded, the excess charges will be neutralized as the ground connection creates an equipotential bonding between the outside of the cage and the environment, so there is no voltage between them and therefore also no field.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The inner face and the inner charge will remain the same, so the field is kept inside.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Static electric shielding effectiveness is largely independent of the geometry of the conductive material; however, the static magnetic fields can penetrate the shield completely.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] In the case of varying electromagnetic fields, the faster the variations are (i.e., the higher the frequencies), the better the material resists magnetic field penetration.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] In this case, the shielding also depends on the electrical conductivity, the magnetic properties of the conductive materials used in the cages, as well as their thicknesses.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] A good example of the effectiveness of a Faraday shield can be obtained from considerations of skin depth.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] With skin depth, the current flowing is mostly on the surface and decays exponentially with depth through the material.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Because a Faraday shield has finite thickness, this determines how well the shield works; a thicker shield can attenuate electromagnetic fields better, and to a lower frequency.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are Faraday shields that have holes in them and are therefore more complex to analyze.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] The shorter the wavelength, the better it passes through a mesh of a given size.
[src:emc-emi/faraday-cage] Thus, to work well at short wavelengths (i.e., high frequencies), the holes in the cage must be smaller than the wavelength of the incident wave.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] A **ferrite bead** – also called a **ferrite block**, **ferrite core**, **ferrite ring**, **EMI filter**, or **ferrite choke** – is a type of choke that suppresses high-frequency electronic noise in electronic circuits.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads employ high-frequency current dissipation in a ferrite ceramic to build high-frequency noise suppression devices.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads prevent electromagnetic interference (EMI) in two directions: *from* a device or *to* a device.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] A conductive cable acts as an antenna – if the device produces radio-frequency energy, this can be *transmitted* through the cable, which acts as an unintentional radiator.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] In this case, the bead is required for regulatory compliance to reduce EMI.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Conversely, if there are other sources of EMI, such as household appliances, the bead prevents the cable from acting as an antenna and *receiving* interference from these other devices.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] This is particularly common on data cables and medical equipment.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Large ferrite beads are commonly seen on external cabling.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] In addition, various smaller ferrite beads are used internally in circuits—on conductors or around the pins of small circuit-board components, such as transistors, connectors, and integrated circuits.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Beads can block low-level unintended radio frequency energy on wires intended to be DC conductors by acting as a low-pass filter.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] For example, on unbalanced coax transmission lines (such as video cables), the cable is designed to contain the signal, and beads can be used to block stray common mode current from using the cable as an antenna while not interfering with the signal carried inside the cable.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] In this use, the bead is a simple form of a balun.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are one of the simplest and least expensive interference filters to install on preexisting electronic cabling.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] For a simple ferrite ring, the wire is wrapped around the core through the center, typically five or seven times.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Clamp-on cores are also available, which attach without wrapping the wire: this type of ferrite core is usually designed so that the wire passes only once through it.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] If the fit is not snug enough, the core can be secured with cable ties, or if the center is large enough, the cabling can loop through one or more times.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] (However, although each loop increases the impedance to high frequencies, it also shifts the frequency of the highest impedance to a lower frequency.) Small ferrite beads can be slipped over component leads to suppress parasitic oscillation.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Surface-mount ferrite beads are available.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Like any other surface-mount inductor, these are soldered into a gap in the printed circuit board trace.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Inside the bead component, a coil of wire runs between layers of ferrite to form a multi-turn inductor around the high-permeability core.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are used as a passive low-pass filter by dissipating radio frequency (RF) energy as heat by design.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors, on the other hand, have no resistance and hence do not dissipate energy as heat.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors only have inductive reactance, which reduces the flow of high-frequency signals by returning some of their energy back towards the signal source (possibly reducing the amount of power drawn) rather than dissipating that energy as heat (as done by the resistance in ferrite beads).
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] While an inductor's reactance may commonly be referred to simply as *impedance*, impedance generally can be any combination of resistance and reactance.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] The geometry and electromagnetic properties of coiled wire over the ferrite bead result in an impedance for high-frequency signals, attenuating high-frequency EMI/RFI electronic noise.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] The energy is either reflected back up the cable or dissipated as low-level heat.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Only in extreme cases is the heat noticeable.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] A ferrite bead can be added to an inductor to improve, in two ways, its ability to block unwanted high frequency noise.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] First, the ferrite concentrates the magnetic field, increasing inductance and, therefore, reactance, which filters out the noise.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Second, if the ferrite is so designed, it can produce an additional loss in the form of resistance in the ferrite itself.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] The ferrite creates an inductor with a very low Q factor.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] This loss heats the ferrite, generally by a negligible amount.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] While the signal level is large enough to cause interference or undesirable effects in sensitive circuits, the energy blocked is typically relatively small.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Depending on the application, the resistive loss characteristic of the ferrite may or may not be desired.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] A design that uses a ferrite bead to improve noise filtering must consider specific circuit characteristics and the frequency range to block.
[src:emc-emi/ferrite-bead] Different ferrite materials have different properties concerning frequency, and the manufacturer's literature helps select the most effective material for the frequency range.
